explanation.body:
Building the heap itself from an array takes O(nlogn) time for the top down approach (it wouldve taken O(n) time if bottom up approach was used)

Doing the sorting itself once a heap is built takes O(nlogn) time

Both the heapify and the sort are part of the general HeapSort function thus we need to add them together. (While O(nlogn) as a final answer is not incorrect, it is better to show the way the function breaks down by separating into the runtime of the two main components when the question offers that to you)

In the best case for quick sort, we always pick the median value of an array to be our pivot index but with truly random arrays, what is the most effective way of picking the median value (without going through to find the median which creates extra overhead time)? There is none, thus there is no best policy

(2,7), (9,5), and (10,3) is one way to achieve this

Video creator accidentally flipped the f and b marker, don't let that confuse you. Enqueue calls always place new items on the end with b and dequeue calls always remove items from the side with f. For the purposes of this class, the f marker is usually on the index with the item that is to be removed next and the b marker is one to the right of the most recently added item (such that the next item to be added will be added where b is).

The black height of the tree is incorrect. The path of the tree going from 10 -> 5 -> 3 -> 4 has a black height of 3, but every other path of the tree has a black height of 2 (the leaf node and leaf null nodes, remember we don't include the root in the black height). To fix this, we can make the 4 node into a red node.
